\section{Property of a skew-symmetric Matrix}
\label{ex:skewsymm}
A matrix $C \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$ is called \textit{skew-symmetric} if
\begin{align*}
C^\top = -C.
\end{align*}
Please show that for a real-valued skew-symmetric matrix $C \in \mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$ it holds
\begin{align*}
x^\top C x = 0
\end{align*}
for all $x \in \mathbb{R}^n$ (i.e., a vector $x$ is always mapped to a perpendicular vector $Cx$).

solution:
{\color{solution}
Let $C\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}$, be a skew-symmetric matrix, i.e. $C^T = -C$.\\Now show, that $x^TCx=0$ holds.
\begin{align*}
\text{\underline{Proof:}}&~x\in\mathbb{R}^n,\\
&x^TCx=(x^TCx)^T=x^TC^Tx=-x^TCx\\
&\Rightarrow~x^TCx=0~~(r\in\mathbb{R},r=-r\Rightarrow r=0)
\end{align*}
}
